Research the state of the art in type annotation coverage analysis for dynamically typed languages, focusing on Python, JavaScript/TypeScript, Ruby, and PHP. For Python specifically, document the following: how mypy, pyright, and pytype calculate type coverage percentages, whether they agree on what counts as typed versus untyped, what the pep484 and pep526 annotation syntax covers and misses, and what the typeshed stub library covers. Research the gradual typing literature: Vitousek et al. on reticulated Python, Rastogi et al. on safe TypeScript, and the broader literature on the migration path from untyped to fully typed codebases. Find empirical studies on whether higher type annotation coverage correlates with fewer runtime errors or bugs — the Gao et al. (2017) study on TypeScript bugs is particularly relevant. For PHP, research the PHPStan and Psalm type coverage tools. For Ruby, research the Sorbet and RBS type system. Document how each ecosystem defines a type coverage percentage (annotated parameters, return types, or variables?) and what thresholds are considered good coverage. Also research what percentage of open-source Python projects on PyPI have any type annotations, and what the distribution looks like, as a baseline for interpreting coverage scores.
